  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3473476430" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3473476430" />
    <a title="India M. Clamp" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24882791-india-m-clamp"><img alt="India M. Clamp" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1382437810p2/24882791.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3473476430?book_show_action=true">Sep 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="India M. Clamp" class="user" itemprop="url" name="India M. Clamp" href="/user/show/24882791-india-m-clamp">India M. Clamp</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3473476430&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3473476430" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17385715397522209336">This was a most auspicious examination, that initially I thought was akin to something scripted out for daytime television. In the course of reading this book, the delight of learning about Dr. Abraham Verghese was enticing---Linda R. Meier and Joan F. Lane Provostial Professor at Stanford University. Those who know me, are aware I am not fond of novels or non-fiction; however, given the aptitude of Verghese’ “scriptio,” I decided there is an opportunity to court erudition (even from non-fiction</span>
  <span id="freeText17385715397522209336" style="display:none">This was a most auspicious examination, that initially I thought was akin to something scripted out for daytime television. In the course of reading this book, the delight of learning about Dr. Abraham Verghese was enticing---Linda R. Meier and Joan F. Lane Provostial Professor at Stanford University. Those who know me, are aware I am not fond of novels or non-fiction; however, given the aptitude of Verghese’ “scriptio,” I decided there is an opportunity to court erudition (even from non-fiction). <br /><br />This novel winds in and out of a physician journey who falls in love with a cadaver who happens to be “with child,” then on to a nurse that finds ways to cajole a man by applying force in a most sensitive area, and then taking his wallet and rendering her own form of justice on the plane. The way Verghese describes his reverence for nuns is one to be noted along with his chapter on “From Fish to Eternity.” Solutions here tug at morals, yet the relief of suffering seems allows an intervention that is incorporeal.<br /><br /><br />“God will judge us, Mr. Harris by--by what we did to relieve the suffering of our fellow human beings. I don’t think God cares what doctrine we embrace. By visiting patients in their home, I...<br />---Abraham Verghese, MD<br /><br />“Neurosurgeons taught me, rules are irrelevant when it comes to suffering…and in that light, I learn.”<br />---India M. Clamp<br /><br /><br />If you enjoy the family escapades rife with expletives, gestures and medical lore, then this is a read that will produce a chemical reaction within for which no pharmaceutical is needed. All physicians’ take the Hippocratic Oath. In that regard “thou shall not cut for stone” which translates to one, cannot take all matters in their non-specialist hands and the delegation of such is needed to render just care for patients. This “prima” novel is perhaps somewhat “in extremis” yet attests to no “vade mecum” sanctioned. <br /><br />Healing with laughter is evident in this exuberant novel “Cutting for Stone by Dr. Abraham Verghese.”It's a substantive, tangible method of rejuvenation via the selective reader entanglement in this novel. Highly recommend this 541-page ode to humor in a busy and economically deprived hospital in New York. This novel attests to the mission of why we go into medicine. Many know the reason is we seek to heal ourselves. Though a surgeon abandoned his own son and the father who betrayed him, Marion and Shiva find their own way and make via a "verrückt" journey. Buy, laugh and heal oneself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17385715397522209336" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

